\f0\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Something that\'92s a weakness of current LLM tracking approaches: weighting.\
\
Because prompt volume isn\'92t a thing, we have to use search data as a proxy in selecting our prompts. But if we stop at that, we end up with a balanced corpus again. \
\
That is, our long-tail query will be weighted with equal importance to our short-tail terms in our final tracking list. We normalize back to an average to reflect performance across the prompts \'96 e.g. \'9356% visibility score\'94.\
\
The problem in this is easy to see when we step back. \
\
How does this change in industries where they have oversized weighting to a specific set of terms in traditional search?\
\
It\'92s highly unlikely that will change dramatically in AI. For that reason, we should weight our prompts accordingly, putting extra emphasis on specific topics rather than aggregated scores.\
\
In practice, this may look like:\
\
A specific report for a short-tail set of prompts\
Callout reporting for the prompts that matter most\
A specific report for long-tail prompts, to not let them dilute the rest\
\
This is critical because even weighting means we normalize our actions. Every improvement looks equal. But in practice that\'92s definitely not true, and we should lean towards the improvements that move the needle for the topic areas that matter most to users.\
\
Yes, ultimately it will all be a guess. But it\'92ll be an educated one, and that\'92s the right way to move forward in the current space we\'92re operating in.}
