A reminder especially with the latest Google Core Update rolling out: One of the biggest mistakes I still see in SEO analysis is assessing performance shifts in isolation \uc0\u55357 \u56391 \cb1 \
\
\cb3 To understand what\'92s really happening, you need to assess all relevant organic search metrics and configurations together together and in context:\cb1 \
\
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Organic traffic trends\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Ranking keyword growth or decline\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Keyword overlap vs competitors\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Backlink profile \cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Engagement signals\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Content depth and coverage\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Category / section-level performance\cb1 \
\cb3 \uc0\u10145 \u65039  Competitors gaining or losing across the same market\cb1 \
\
\cb3 This is why I find competitor comparison dashboards genuinely useful when doing SEO analysis: it helps you analyze the different metrics next to each other faster, to identify the patterns that matter faster. \cb1 \
\
\cb3 I\'92ve been using the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.linkedin.com/company/semrush/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\b \cf4 Semrush}} \'93Competitor Comparison\'94 report in their Enterprise suite for this, since it lets you compare your site vs competitors across organic traffic, ranking keywords, backlinks, engagement, and content related signals in one place.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 That broader context is especially useful when you need to answer where you're specifically falling behind, against whom and what's driving the gap. \cb1 \
\
\cb3 If you're already using Semrush: Check out it. If not, this is another useful dashboard to try out. \cb1 \
\
